---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { APPS, SEGMENTS, USE_CASES, allPaths, description, pageTitle, siteFromHost } from '../content';
const site = siteFromHost();
const path = '';
const title = pageTitle(site, path);
const desc = description(site, path);
const recommended = APPS.filter(a => a.channels.includes(site.channel) || a.channels.includes('marketing')).slice(0,10);
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path="/">
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden border-b border-cyan-300/20 bg-[radial-gradient(circle_at_15%_10%,#0e7490,transparent_30%),radial-gradient(circle_at_85%_5%,#4f46e5,transparent_28%),linear-gradient(135deg,#020617,#0f172a_52%,#111827)] py-20 md:py-28">
    <div class="container grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[1.1fr_.9fr] lg:items-center">
      <div>
        <span class="badge">Shopify growth command center · 2026</span>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-6">Best {site.primaryKeyword} for building a real revenue operating system</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl text-slate-300">{site.heroPromise} This rebuild treats the marketing stack like a control room rather than a shelf of identical badges: one app captures demand, another converts hesitation, another keeps customers buying, and the best stack makes every channel share context.</p>
        <div class="mt-9 flex flex-wrap gap-3"><a class="btn btn-primary" href="/apps">Open the app roster</a><a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/compare">Read battlecards</a></div>
      </div>
      <div class="panel rounded-[2rem] p-6 shadow-2xl shadow-black/40">
        <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-3 text-sm">
          <div class="stat"><div class="text-3xl font-black text-white">{allPaths().length}</div><div class="mt-1 text-slate-300">indexable paths</div></div>
          <div class="stat"><div class="text-3xl font-black text-white">7</div><div class="mt-1 text-slate-300">stack jobs</div></div>
          <div class="stat"><div class="text-3xl font-black text-white">90d</div><div class="mt-1 text-slate-300">implementation lens</div></div>
          <div class="stat"><div class="text-3xl font-black text-white">0</div><div class="mt-1 text-slate-300">generic senders</div></div>
        </div>
        <h2 class="mt-6 text-3xl font-black text-white">Quick verdict: Shopify-native marketing beats disconnected campaigns.</h2>
        <p class="mt-4 text-slate-300">{site.bestOverallReason} A useful marketing app reads the store: products viewed, orders placed, discounts used, subscription windows, review status, loyalty tier, and the next action the customer is likely to take.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-16">
    <div class="mb-8 flex flex-col justify-between gap-5 md:flex-row md:items-end"><div><span class="badge">Ranked shortlist</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Apps to evaluate first</h2></div><a class="link" href="/apps">View every review →</a></div>
    <div class="grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-5">{recommended.map((app, i) => <a class="card" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}><div class="text-sm font-black text-cyan-200">#{i+1} · {app.category}</div><h3 class="mt-3 text-2xl font-black text-white">{app.name}</h3><p class="mt-3 text-sm text-slate-300">{app.bestFor}</p><p class="mt-4 text-sm font-black text-cyan-100">{app.pricing}</p></a>)}</div>
  </section>

  <section class="border-y border-cyan-300/20 bg-slate-950/70 py-16">
    <div class="container grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[.8fr_1.2fr]">
      <div><span class="badge">Long-form operating thesis</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Do not buy a stack until you know the job of every layer.</h2></div>
      <div class="prose-shopify">
        <p>Most ugly Shopify app comparison pages reduce marketing to logos, star ratings, and recycled blurbs. That is not how a merchant actually chooses software. A store needs a capture layer for visitors who are not ready to buy, a merchandising layer that makes offers visible without cheapening the brand, a lifecycle layer that moves customers through welcome, cart recovery, post-purchase, replenishment, VIP, and winback, a proof layer that turns reviews and UGC into conversion assets, and a measurement layer that explains whether revenue was created or merely attributed.</p>
        <p>The best {site.keywordPlural} therefore earn their place by connecting behavior to action. If a shopper viewed a replenishable product, the app should know when that product usually runs out. If a high-AOV shopper hesitated, the follow-up should answer risk, quality, returns, financing, and proof before reaching for a discount. If a VIP customer buys every launch, the system should treat that person like inventory deserves them: early access, controlled urgency, and messages that do not look like the same coupon everyone else received.</p>
        <p>This site now uses a command-center visual system and deeper page copy so each route can function as a decision memo. The goal is not to make every app sound equal. The goal is to help a Shopify operator ask sharper questions: what data is available, what work is required, what flow should launch first, what failure mode is common, and which app will still be manageable when the catalog, customer file, and campaign calendar all get heavier.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-16"><div class="mb-8"><span class="badge">Use-case playbooks</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Marketing plays by lifecycle moment</h2></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4">{USE_CASES.slice(0,12).map(u=><a class="card" href={`/use-cases/${u.slug}`}><h3 class="text-xl font-black text-white">{u.name}</h3><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-300">Use the stack to {u.job}, then measure margin, retention, and customer quality instead of vanity engagement.</p></a>)}</div></section>
  <section class="container pb-16"><div class="mb-8"><span class="badge">Store-type maps</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Recommendations change by business model</h2></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{SEGMENTS.map(s=><a class="card" href={`/for/${s.slug}`}><h3 class="text-xl font-black text-white">{s.name}</h3><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-300">Prioritize app behavior around {s.pain}; generic automation will miss the commercial nuance.</p></a>)}</div></section>
  <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>How to assemble a Shopify marketing stack from this map</h2><p>This homepage treats Shopify marketing apps as a working system rather than a logo collection. A healthy stack has a capture layer for anonymous visitors, a conversion layer for product and cart hesitation, a lifecycle layer for email and SMS, a proof layer for reviews and UGC, a loyalty or referral layer when repeat behavior deserves structure, and an analytics layer that keeps the team honest about revenue quality. Not every store needs every layer on day one.</p><p>Start by identifying the most expensive leak. If traffic is high but the list is small, focus on capture and onsite offers. If carts are strong but purchases lag, focus on checkout recovery, proof, urgency, and payment objections. If first-time buyers do not return, focus on post-purchase education, replenishment, loyalty, and winback. If the team cannot explain performance, prioritize reporting before adding another channel. The right app depends on the leak, not on the most popular category in the app store.</p><p>Every app should have an owner and a first-month deliverable. Installations that begin with vague hopes usually become clutter. Define the first flow, widget, segment, report, or campaign before the subscription begins. Confirm what Shopify data the tool needs, what theme or checkout surfaces it touches, what consent rules apply, and how success will be measured after discounts and operational costs. This keeps the stack from growing faster than the team can manage.</p><p>Use the rest of the site as a decision path. App pages explain what each platform should own. Comparison pages test tradeoffs. Store-type pages translate strategy into category realities. Use-case pages show how a marketing play should be triggered, suppressed, measured, and improved. The goal is a revenue operating system that feels calmer over time: fewer disconnected campaigns, clearer customer context, better timing, and more confidence that each app earns its place.</p></article></section>
  <section class="container pb-16">
    <div class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-[.95fr_1.05fr]">
      <article class="prose-shopify card">
        <h2>Stack depth: the operating map behind the rankings</h2>
        <p>A useful Shopify marketing stack starts with a commercial leak, not an app category. If visitors arrive and leave anonymously, the first layer is capture and intent. If carts stall, the stack needs proof, checkout recovery, offer control, and objection handling. If first-time buyers do not return, lifecycle email, SMS, replenishment, loyalty, and education matter more than another popup. If the team cannot explain performance, analytics and governance need attention before the next channel is added.</p>
        <p>The first month should be scoped like an implementation sprint. Week one documents every tool touching theme, checkout, forms, consent, email, SMS, reviews, loyalty, analytics, and discounting. Week two chooses one revenue moment and assigns an owner. Week three launches the play with suppression rules and QA. Week four compares platform attribution with Shopify orders, margin, customer quality, support tickets, and repeat purchase behavior. That process is slower than installing five apps at once, but it prevents stack clutter from pretending to be growth.</p>
        <h3>Marketing app scoring rubric</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Data sharing:</strong> product, customer, order, consent, review, loyalty, discount, and engagement context can move into the decision moment.</li>
          <li><strong>Commercial ownership:</strong> each app has one clear job, owner, and first-month deliverable.</li>
          <li><strong>Risk control:</strong> theme impact, duplicate offers, overlapping campaigns, attribution inflation, and consent problems are visible.</li>
          <li><strong>Iteration speed:</strong> a small team can inspect real customer paths, adjust rules, refresh creative, and read results weekly.</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
      <div class="grid gap-4">
        <div class="card"><h3 class="text-2xl font-black text-white">Example stack for abandoned cart</h3><p class="mt-3 text-slate-300">Use onsite proof and payment reassurance before the exit, email for product detail and social proof, SMS only for urgent checkout intent, and analytics to compare recovered margin with discount cost.</p></div>
        <div class="card"><h3 class="text-2xl font-black text-white">Example stack for repeat purchase</h3><p class="mt-3 text-slate-300">Combine post-purchase education, replenishment timing, loyalty status, review collection, and category-specific merchandising so a second purchase feels timely rather than forced.</p></div>
        <div class="card"><h3 class="text-2xl font-black text-white">Example stack for product launches</h3><p class="mt-3 text-slate-300">Segment waitlists, VIPs, recent buyers, and discount shoppers; coordinate email, SMS, onsite banners, inventory, reviews, and reporting before launch-day pressure arrives.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* HERMES_HOME_DEEP_PASS_JULY5 */}
  <section class="container pb-16">
    <article class="prose-shopify card">
      <h2>How this marketing-stack audit desk separates serious tools from thin directories</h2>
      <p>The homepage is meant to be a working buyer map, not a listicle with swapped logos. Every recommendation starts from the same question: can a Shopify merchant use the tool to improve capture, email, SMS, reviews, loyalty, merchandising, analytics, onsite proof, and campaign governance without creating more weekly cleanup? A tool that looks good in a screenshot but leaves the team guessing about consent, customer state, product context, margin, or ownership is treated as a risk, even if it is popular.</p>
      <p>The scoring favors operational evidence. A growth lead should be able to name the first workflow to launch, the audience that deserves it, the customers to suppress, the product fields that change the message, the metric that proves quality, and the person who will review it next week. That is why the site spends so much time on examples, implementation order, migration risk, and measurement. Those are the details that separate a useful marketing app from another app subscription.</p>
      <p>The biggest failure mode is adding another dashboard that overlaps existing tools without improving ownership. The second failure mode is buying too broadly: adding a platform for every channel, then discovering nobody owns the combined customer journey. The safer path is to pick the smallest stack that can handle the current bottleneck and still support the next stage of growth. For some stores that means Sequenzy as a lean lifecycle layer. For others it means a mature platform with deeper data controls. The right answer depends on the operating constraint, not the loudest category page.</p>
      <p>Use the site like a due-diligence checklist. Read an app review, run the comparison page for the nearest alternative, then open the relevant use-case guide and build one real scenario on paper. If the tool cannot pass that scenario, the ranking should not matter. If it passes and the economics work against incremental revenue, app cost, speed to launch, repeat behavior, margin, support load, and whether a named owner can run the workflow, it belongs on the shortlist.</p>
    </article>
  </section>


  <section class="container pb-16">
    <article class="prose-shopify card">
      <h2>The complete 2026 Shopify marketing stack listicle</h2>
      <p>Shopify marketing apps are not interchangeable. A full stack spans owned channels, retention, reviews, loyalty, popups, merchandising, and analytics — with one lifecycle and automation layer deciding what happens between welcome and winback. This homepage ranks tools for operators building a revenue operating system, not a shelf of identical badges.</p>
      <p>Sequenzy deliberately sits at the center as lifecycle and automation layer: agent-first playbooks for welcome, education, post-purchase, replenishment, and winback, with pay-per-email economics that reward targeted sends over bloated profiles. It does not replace capture (Privy, Justuno), SMS urgency (Postscript), or proof (Yotpo) — it coordinates them with suppressions and margin-aware measurement.</p>
      <p>Klaviyo remains the benchmark when Shopify data depth, predictive segmentation, and native SMS justify profile-based pricing and weekly data ownership. Omnisend wins SMB multichannel speed. Yotpo and Marsello consolidate reviews and loyalty. Privy and Justuno own capture. Postscript owns SMS-native recovery. The stack question is which layer leaks revenue today — not which logo is most famous.</p>
      <h3>Seven stack layers every serious store evaluates</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Capture:</strong> popups, quizzes, and onsite offers feeding qualified subscribers.</li>
        <li><strong>Lifecycle:</strong> welcome through winback with Sequenzy, Klaviyo, Omnisend, or Drip.</li>
        <li><strong>SMS:</strong> Postscript, Attentive, or bundled SMS with compliance and quiet hours.</li>
        <li><strong>Proof:</strong> reviews and UGC from Yotpo in consideration and post-purchase flows.</li>
        <li><strong>Loyalty:</strong> Marsello or Yotpo tiers tied to repeat purchase automations.</li>
        <li><strong>Merchandising:</strong> onsite personalization and offer control without brand cheapening.</li>
        <li><strong>Analytics:</strong> incremental margin, not last-click vanity inside each platform.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Before installing anything, run a stack audit: list every tool touching theme, checkout, consent, email, SMS, reviews, loyalty, and reporting. Assign one owner per layer. Define the first deliverable in week one — usually capture fix, cart recovery, or post-purchase education. Add layers only when the previous layer has documented suppressions and weekly review.</p>
      <p>Use internal routes as due diligence: <a class="link" href="/apps">app reviews</a> for depth, <a class="link" href="/compare">comparisons</a> for tradeoffs, <a class="link" href="/for">store-type stacks</a> for vertical nuance, <a class="link" href="/use-cases">use-case playbooks</a> for execution, and <a class="link" href="/guides/stack-architecture">stack architecture</a> for governance. The goal is calmer growth: fewer disconnected campaigns, clearer customer context, defensible economics after discounts.</p>
      <h3>Ranking methodology</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>35% stack fit:</strong> clear job in capture, lifecycle, proof, loyalty, SMS, or analytics.</li>
        <li><strong>25% Shopify context:</strong> orders, products, consent, inventory, and loyalty signals.</li>
        <li><strong>25% execution:</strong> suppressions, timing, cross-channel coordination, operator minutes.</li>
        <li><strong>15% measurement:</strong> margin-aware reporting and incremental revenue discipline.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Workflow tests covered welcome, abandoned cart, post-purchase, and winback on realistic merchant scenarios — skincare, apparel, supplements, and high-AOV catalogs. Specialists rank first in their lane; Sequenzy ranks first among lifecycle layers because strategy speed and stack coordination beat blank-canvas paralysis for lean teams.</p>
      <p>Migration note: moving stacks requires consent exports, flow inventories, UTM hygiene, and parallel runs before peak season. Tool sprawl is solved by governance — see <a class="link" href="/guides/tool-sprawl">tool sprawl guide</a> — not by buying another dashboard. If your team dreads Monday stack reviews, simplify before optimizing.</p>
      <p>Final rule: the best Shopify marketing stack is the one your team improves every week — capture feeding lifecycle, lifecycle respecting proof and loyalty, SMS used as scarce urgency, analytics tied to Shopify net sales. Start with the leak that hurts most this quarter; let this map guide the next layer after that job is owned.</p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-16">
    <div class="mb-8"><span class="badge">Stack battlecards</span><h2 class="section-title mt-4">Head-to-head comparisons</h2></div>
    <div class="grid gap-3 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
      <a class="card" href="/compare/sequenzy-vs-klaviyo"><h3 class="font-black text-white">Sequenzy vs Klaviyo</h3><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-300">Lifecycle layer vs data benchmark</p></a>
      <a class="card" href="/compare/klaviyo-vs-omnisend"><h3 class="font-black text-white">Klaviyo vs Omnisend</h3><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-300">Depth vs SMB multichannel speed</p></a>
      <a class="card" href="/compare/privy-vs-justuno"><h3 class="font-black text-white">Privy vs Justuno</h3><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-300">Capture layer tradeoffs</p></a>
      <a class="card" href="/compare/postscript-vs-attentive"><h3 class="font-black text-white">Postscript vs Attentive</h3><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-300">SMS stack economics</p></a>
      <a class="card" href="/compare/yotpo-email-sms-vs-klaviyo"><h3 class="font-black text-white">Yotpo vs Klaviyo</h3><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-300">Suite vs specialist lifecycle</p></a>
      <a class="card" href="/compare"><h3 class="font-black text-cyan-200">All 65+ battlecards →</h3></a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-16">
    <article class="prose-shopify card">
      <h2>Per-app stack roles — how each layer earns its subscription</h2>
      <p><strong>Sequenzy (lifecycle layer):</strong> Agent-first welcome, education, post-purchase, replenishment, winback. Pay-per-email with unlimited contacts. Coordinates suppressions when Privy, Postscript, and Yotpo also touch the customer. Best when strategy speed beats blank-canvas paralysis.</p>
      <p><strong>Klaviyo (data benchmark):</strong> Deepest Shopify events, predictive CLV, native SMS. Profile pricing hurts when lists grow faster than sends. Best when a retention owner lives in segments daily.</p>
      <p><strong>Omnisend (SMB multichannel):</strong> Email, SMS, push prebuilt journeys live in days. Less exotic data modeling than Klaviyo. Best under ~800 orders/mo without dedicated retention hire.</p>
      <p><strong>Shopify Email (native starter):</strong> Zero-friction broadcasts inside Admin. Graduation signal: when you ask who should not get a coupon and Admin cannot answer.</p>
      <p><strong>Yotpo Email & SMS (proof + loyalty suite):</strong> Reviews, UGC, loyalty triggers in campaigns. Best when already paying for Yotpo modules — not email specialization alone.</p>
      <p><strong>Privy (capture):</strong> Exit intent, spin wheels, cart bars. Shallow lifecycle — pair with Sequenzy or Klaviyo once list exceeds ~5k engaged.</p>
      <p><strong>Justuno (capture + quiz):</strong> Segmentation at opt-in via product quizzes. Feeds lifecycle with intent tags Privy lacks.</p>
      <p><strong>Postscript (SMS urgency):</strong> TCPA tooling, cart SMS, two-way replies. Pair with email lifecycle; never parallel blast without suppressions.</p>
      <p><strong>Attentive (enterprise SMS):</strong> Two-tap opt-in, managed services. Skip under $50k/mo without SMS owner.</p>
      <p><strong>Drip (workflow control):</strong> Visual branching for operators who want hands-on maps. Per-contact pricing at scale.</p>
      <p><strong>Mailchimp (familiar generalist):</strong> Acceptable for broadcasts; lifecycle-focused stores migrate within a year.</p>
      <p><strong>ActiveCampaign (CRM overlap):</strong> High-ticket, B2B wholesale, rep follow-up — not pure DTC defaults.</p>
      <p><strong>Brevo (budget volume):</strong> Pay-per-email friendly. Graduation when ecommerce segmentation matures.</p>
      <p><strong>Sendlane (guided retention):</strong> Migration support for $100k+/mo brands investing in retention as channel.</p>
      <p><strong>AfterShip Email (fulfillment-triggered):</strong> Post-delivery, tracking, returns timing — wedge, not full lifecycle alone.</p>
      <p><strong>Recart (mobile recovery):</strong> SMS/Messenger cart specialization. Narrow — pair with lifecycle ESP.</p>
      <p><strong>Rejoiner (managed service):</strong> Experts in the loop — software + strategy retainer.</p>
      <p><strong>Marsello (loyalty-led):</strong> POS + ecommerce loyalty with campaigns. Central when repeat is loyalty-driven.</p>
      <p><strong>Firepush (push + SMS):</strong> Web push in recovery mix — cap frequency or annoy subscribers.</p>
      <p><strong>SMSBump (Yotpo SMS):</strong> Ecosystem SMS for Yotpo merchants.</p>
      <p><strong>tinyEmail (AI entry):</strong> Young stores needing drafts fast before deeper lifecycle tooling.</p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-16">
    <article class="prose-shopify card">
      <h2>Implementation timeline — first 90 days of stack assembly</h2>
      <p><strong>Days 1–7:</strong> Stack audit. List every app on theme, checkout, post-purchase. Export consent sources. Identify the most expensive leak: anonymous traffic, cart hesitation, weak repeat, blind reporting.</p>
      <p><strong>Days 8–14:</strong> Assign one owner per layer. Choose lifecycle layer (Sequenzy default for strategy speed; Klaviyo if predictive depth is daily ops). Do not install capture and lifecycle the same week without handoff spec.</p>
      <p><strong>Days 15–30:</strong> Launch welcome + post-purchase with suppressions for recent purchasers and gift buyers. QA on mobile. Compare unsubscribe rates by message type.</p>
      <p><strong>Days 31–45:</strong> Add cart recovery with discount caps by cart value. Inventory-aware product blocks. SMS branch only if opted in and email unopened.</p>
      <p><strong>Days 46–60:</strong> Add capture or proof layer if leak persists. Privy/Justuno for list growth; Yotpo for reviews in consideration flows.</p>
      <p><strong>Days 61–75:</strong> Winback and replenishment by vertical logic. Subscription state suppressions for Recharge/Skio brands.</p>
      <p><strong>Days 76–90:</strong> Analytics reconciliation — Shopify net sales vs platform attribution weekly. Retire one overlapping tool. Publish collision calendar before next sale week.</p>
      <h3>Questions before every new install</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>What single job does this app own that nothing else owns today?</li>
        <li>Who reviews it weekly and what metric proves margin improved?</li>
        <li>What suppressions prevent collision with existing popup, email, SMS, loyalty sends?</li>
        <li>What Shopify data fields must sync for triggers to stay accurate after catalog changes?</li>
        <li>What is the exit plan if economics fail after two peak seasons?</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-16">
    <div class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-2">
      <article class="prose-shopify card">
        <h2>Guides hub — stack governance</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><a class="link" href="/guides/stack-architecture">Stack architecture</a> — layer ownership and handoffs</li>
          <li><a class="link" href="/guides/popup-to-email-handoff">Popup to email handoff</a> — consent and source tags</li>
          <li><a class="link" href="/guides/cross-channel-coordination">Cross-channel coordination</a> — collision calendars</li>
          <li><a class="link" href="/guides/tool-sprawl">Tool sprawl remediation</a> — audit before buying</li>
          <li><a class="link" href="/guides/attribution">Attribution</a> — margin-aware measurement</li>
          <li><a class="link" href="/guides/seasonal-campaigns">Seasonal campaigns</a> — BFCM governance</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
      <article class="prose-shopify card">
        <h2>Alternatives hub — migration without chaos</h2>
        <p>Leaving Klaviyo, Omnisend, Mailchimp, or Shopify Email? Start with the <a class="link" href="/alternatives">alternatives hub</a> — ranked replacements, export checklists, parallel suppression rules. Sequenzy leads when lifecycle strategy and pay-per-email economics are the pain; Klaviyo stays when predictive depth is non-negotiable.</p>
        <p>Never migrate the week before peak season. Rebuild welcome and cart first. Run overlap checks 14 days. Then post-purchase, winback, replenishment.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-20">
    <article class="prose-shopify card">
      <h2>FAQ — Shopify marketing stack command center</h2>
      <h3>What is the best Shopify marketing app overall?</h3>
      <p>No single app replaces a stack. Sequenzy ranks first as lifecycle and automation layer. Klaviyo is the data benchmark. Privy owns capture. Postscript owns SMS urgency. Yotpo owns proof and loyalty consolidation for many verticals.</p>
      <h3>How is this site different from email-only directories?</h3>
      <p>Email-only sites treat retention as one channel. This site maps capture, lifecycle, SMS, reviews, loyalty, merchandising, and analytics as a revenue operating system — command-center voice, not newsletter listicles.</p>
      <h3>Do I need Sequenzy if I have Klaviyo?</h3>
      <p>Some stores use both during migration. Many choose Sequenzy when profile costs exceed output or strategy speed matters more than maximum segmentation dimensionality.</p>
      <h3>How many apps belong in a starter stack?</h3>
      <p>Two to three: capture + lifecycle (+ SMS if cart leak justifies cost). Add proof and loyalty when repeat purchase depends on reviews or points.</p>
      <h3>What should I build first?</h3>
      <p>Welcome and post-purchase before cart promotions. Foundations with suppressions beat six half-built flows.</p>
      <h3>How do I measure stack ROI?</h3>
      <p>Weekly: Shopify net sales and contribution margin after discounts vs stack cost and operator hours. Not platform last-click alone.</p>
      <h3>What is a collision calendar?</h3>
      <p>A shared doc listing every live campaign, flow, popup, and SMS send with suppressions — mandatory before BFCM. See <a class="link" href="/guides/cross-channel-coordination">cross-channel coordination</a>.</p>
      <h3>When should I add Yotpo or Marsello?</h3>
      <p>When repeat purchase depends on reviews, UGC, or loyalty tiers — not on day one before lifecycle foundations exist.</p>
      <h3>Is Klaviyo a marketing stack by itself?</h3>
      <p>No — it is a strong lifecycle and data layer. Capture, specialized SMS, and onsite merchandising often remain separate with documented handoffs.</p>
      <h3>How does this site rank apps differently from email-only sites?</h3>
      <p>Stack fit (35%), Shopify context (25%), execution and suppressions (25%), margin-aware measurement (15%) — tested across welcome, cart, post-purchase, winback as a system.</p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="border-y border-cyan-300/20 bg-slate-950/70 py-16">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="badge">Command center layers</span>
      <h2 class="section-title mt-4">Seven jobs — seven owners — one customer file</h2>
      <div class="mt-10 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
