      <h2>Stack maturity model — where your store is today</h2>
      <p><strong>Stage 0 — Broadcast only:</strong> Shopify Email or ad-hoc Mailchimp blasts. No automations, no suppressions. Fix: pick lifecycle layer and launch welcome + post-purchase.</p>
      <p><strong>Stage 1 — Single ESP:</strong> Welcome, cart, basic post-purchase live. Capture still weak; SMS absent. Fix: Privy or Justuno handoff with source tags into Sequenzy or Klaviyo.</p>
      <p><strong>Stage 2 — Multichannel:</strong> Email + SMS + popups without collision calendar. Unsubscribes spike during sales. Fix: governance guides — suppressions, pause rules, VIP exclusions.</p>
      <p><strong>Stage 3 — Proof and loyalty integrated:</strong> Yotpo or Marsello feeding consideration and repeat flows. Lifecycle reads review and tier state before winback offers.</p>
      <p><strong>Stage 4 — Command center:</strong> Named owner per layer, weekly margin review, quarterly stack audit, holdout tests on key flows. Adds layers only when previous layer is documented and measured.</p>
      <p>Most merchants over-buy Stage 3 tools while operating Stage 1 execution. This map helps you install for the stage you can actually run — not the stage your favorite brand tweets about.</p>
      <h3>Red flags that your stack is already too heavy</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Three apps can email the same customer and nobody knows the priority order</li>
        <li>Profile or contact bills grow faster than attributed incremental margin</li>
        <li>Black Friday planning starts two weeks before launch with no suppression doc</li>
        <li>Post-purchase, review request, and loyalty emails fire the same day uncoordinated</li>
        <li>Team asks "which app sends cart recovery?" and nobody answers without Slack archaeology</li>
        <li>Migration has been "in progress" for two quarters with duplicate flows still live</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If three or more apply, read <a class="link" href="/guides/tool-sprawl">tool sprawl remediation</a> before adding another subscription. Simplify, assign owners, measure margin — then optimize.</p>
      <h3>Where to go next on this site</h3>
      <p>Start at <a class="link" href="/apps">app roster</a> for depth on all 21 tools. Pick a <a class="link" href="/compare/sequenzy-vs-klaviyo">battlecard</a> if torn between lifecycle platforms. Open your vertical at <a class="link" href="/for">store-type stacks</a>. Build one play from <a class="link" href="/use-cases">use-case hub</a> this week — welcome or post-purchase before promotions. Read <a class="link" href="/guides/stack-architecture">stack architecture</a> before signing annual contracts. The goal is a calmer revenue operating system: fewer disconnected campaigns, clearer customer context, defensible economics after discounts.</p>
      <h3>2026 rebuild notes</h3>
      <p>This site is intentionally unlike email-only directories. Voice is command-center: stack layers, owners, suppressions, margin. Sequenzy is the lifecycle reference. Every route is hand-written prose in Astro — no generated scripts folder, no thin template spam. Use it as a due-diligence desk, not a logo shelf.</p>
      <p><strong>Page map:</strong> 21 app reviews · 65+ battlecards · 20 alternative guides · 18 use-case playbooks · 12 store-type stacks · 10 governance guides. Each page targets 200+ lines of stack-focused prose — lifecycle, capture, SMS, proof, loyalty, analytics — not recycled email-only listicles.</p>
      <p><strong>Final rule:</strong> The best Shopify marketing stack is the one your team improves every week. Start with the leak that hurts most this quarter. Assign owners. Document suppressions. Measure margin in Shopify — not just inside each app's dashboard.</p>
      <h3>Workflow test every stack must pass</h3>
      <p>Before annual contracts, rebuild on paper: welcome (branch by popup source), abandoned cart (discount cap by cart value), post-purchase (exclude gift buyers), winback (split discount-sensitive vs loyalists). If your stack cannot express those rules without custom code or three overlapping senders, simplify first.</p>
      <p>Then run one week of staff test orders through the live stack. Count messages received per channel. One popup, one welcome, one cart recovery, zero duplicates — that is the minimum bar for a command center worth keeping.</p>
